Current quantum computing hardware imposes strict constraints on two-qubit gate operations, limiting their application to specific qubit pairs. This leads to a structural mismatch between quantum circuits and hardware limitations. Quantum circuit mapping addresses this issue by inserting SWAP gates to enable logical circuit equivalence. In the Noisy Intermediate-Scale Quantum (NISQ) era, minimizing the number of additional gates is crucial to reduce circuit error rates. We propose LARBE (Look-Ahead Rewards and Biased Exploration), a deep reinforcement learning framework utilizing graph neural networks to encode quantum circuits. The look-ahead reward mechanism enables intelligent trade-offs between immediate and future mapping benefits, while the biased exploration incorporates heuristic rules to accelerate training convergence. Benchmarking against the SABRE algorithm demonstrates performance improvements ranging from 5.83% to 17.57% on several common hardware topologies.